<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="7314338991b0242194ea5e63854752a3" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> What happened to the Dwarves?<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.57)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955'>Kyle "Master Kyle" McEachron</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1955&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 18, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <br />
Alright. Yes, question that’s been haunting me since the release of TTT. What did happen to the dwarves? “Some things that should not have been forgotten were lost”-Galadriel. <br />
I think this phrase can apply to the dwarves after TTT. I might see a few dwarven decks before, but after the release of the Two Towers, they disappeared completely. Opening TTT packs, you probably considered the dwarf rares you got as the not so good rares, but hopefully you won’t think so now.<br />
<br />
I am going to do a card by card analysis of each dwarf card from TTT. For those of you reading this at 1 AM, I suggest you get some sleep and read this some other time unless you just had an insane of amount of caffeine or are intent to read it to the end. Please, however, do not rate this deck until you have read the whole thing! Let’s go…<br />
<br />
Axe of Erebor (unique) <br />
Dwarven Possession. Hand Weapon.<br />
Bearer must be Gimli. He is damage +1. Skirmish:<br />
Discard a [Dwarf] condition or a card stacked on<br />
a [Dwarf] condition to make Gimli strength +1.<br />
Strength: +2<br />
Twilight Cost: 2<br />
<br />
The new version of Gimli’s Axe is obviously suited for the new Two Towers cards. The theme of Dwarves is card stacking. A risky theme, but could be very useful. Each stacked card could mean an additional strength for Gimli. This works similar to Boromir, My Brother, but differently at the same time. The Axe gives him a flat out Str +2 and Dm +1.<br />
The text can also let you discard dwarven conditions or stacked cards to boost him. Ok, let’s look at conditions. You might think, what condition would be worth discarding to give Gimli a measly strength +1. How about Till Durin Wakes Again? If you’ve passed site 7, there are no more undergrounds, so it’s better off in your discard pile, so why not make good use of it? Any others? What about Dwarven Heart? Maybe not gone, but the faster you can get it off your dwarf after healing, the better. Axe of Erebor helps you do that. What if you have a stack of 6 useless cards on Ever My Heart Rises (I’ll go into more detail about that later). That’s a potential +6 strength there. <br />
<br />
Best Company<br />
Dwarven Event<br />
Skirmish: Make a Dwarf strength +2 <br />
(or +4 if at a battleground).<br />
Twilight Cost: 0<br />
<br />
As Dwarven events go, this is about as good as they get next to Flurry of Blows which may be used less due to the addition of Grima. Come to think of it, I think that’s a big reason why you people aren’t using dwarves. I’ll address him later. Anyways, it gives him a +2 bonus, but will normally, however, give him +4. Do you remember how you could rig every site except for 4 and 5 to be a forest or river in fellowship? Well, you can do the same thing with two towers and battlegrounds. There is a battleground for every site except 3 and 8, I believe. Some may argue that Khazad Ai-menu is better. It really has it’s own use, but since Gimli with his axe is already damage +2, I prefer the extra strength. Did I forget to mention that every site 5 is a battleground, thus this card will work every time at 5.<br />
<br />
Come Here Lad<br />
Dwarven Event<br />
Fellowship: Stack the top 2 cards from <br />
your draw deck on a [Dwarven] condition<br />
that has a card already stacked on it.<br />
Twilight Cost: 0<br />
<br />
This card is obviously made for the stack strategy. Ok. Where would be the best place to stack those cards? Ever my Heart Rises would give you 2 more cards for a total of 8 cards to choose from. Not bad. Courtesy of My Hall, however, could potentially, mean 2 more wounds healed off your dwarves if those two top cards are free peoples. Also, if unneeded, they can be shuffled back or used as fuel for Gimli’s Axe.<br />
<br />
Courtesy of My Hall (unique)<br />
Dwarven Condition<br />
Plays to your support area. When you play this<br />
Condition, stack a card from your discard pile here.<br />
Fellowship: Discard a Free peoples card stacked here<br />
to heal a dwarf.<br />
Twilight Cost: 1<br />
<br />
Dwarven Foresight<br />
Dwarven Event<br />
Fellowship: Spot a Dwarf to take a Free Peoples<br />
Card stacked on a [Dwarven] condition into hand.<br />
Twilight cost: 0<br />
<br />
The reason I mentioned these 2 cards together is because they a very obvious combo. Go grab your favorite or most needed free peoples card from discard with courtesy and use Foresight to take it into hand. Also, the Courtesy gives you the benefit of using the card if no Foresight shows up and pitching it back to heal your dwarf. The Foresight, when played in the right deck, is an easy card to get rid of if the combo never comes. This combo will prove very useful since the dwarven strategies discard top cards a lot, you may accidentally lose something you wanted. Use this combo to get it back. Also, I should remind you, I would use Courteous Halfling Frodo. If your opponent played discard, you might be in trouble. Just a suggestion. You must play a large deck with dwarves because once it gets going, it travels through deck at the speed of light. So, in a way, this combo is a way of getting the cards you need faster. Also, there’s no reason this card has to be used in a dwarf deck. Even with just Gimli, you can get back a PATHs you used or discarded a while back or get a Cliffs or Bowmen. There’s probably a lot more great cards to work with it. <br />
<br />
Ever My Heart Rises (unique)<br />
Dwarven Condition<br />
Tale. Plays to your support area. When you play this<br />
condition, reveal the top 6 cards of your draw deck<br />
and stack them here. Fellowship: Spot a Dwarf and<br />
discard the top card of your draw deck to take a<br />
Free Peoples card stacked here into hand.<br />
Twilight Cost: 3<br />
<br />
Yes, I know. It’s a bummer. This card only lets you get free peoples off the condition. Believe it of not, though, this card actually does help your minion side. How? Well, by taking the FPs cards and shuffling the rest back with cards like Rest by Blind Night or Restless Axe, you can create what is known as a deck imbalance. In this case, it is getting and playing all your free peoples cards early or all at once. How does that help? Well, if you get/play all the free peoples at once, chances are you will get all your shadow at once. This is particularly useful for you Moria players, who often rely on large numbers of minions in hand. Once the imbalance is set in motion, you can play that Goblin Scimitar with the knowledge that you will probably draw a minion. Not only that, but if your swarming plan goes wrong, you may still have a chance of repeating the process. The trick is to use cards like this to cycle through your deck quickly so you don’t miss your opportunity. Again, this can be used with other decks. It doesn’t have to be dwarf related. A good example of this is =tarkin=’s Gimli superstar deck. It uses 4 of this card. It can help players with larger decks go through them faster. It’s kind of drawing mechanism, but you don’t have to worry about clogging your hand with useless cards. The drawback… Condition discard. However, since getting cards from here is a fellowship action, you can still grab the ones you need when you play it before your opponent can get their hands on it. Also, it’s a Tale (Gloin anyone?)<br />
<br />
From the Armory<br />
Dwarven Condition.<br />
Plays to your support area. Skirmish: Exert<br />
a Dwarf and stack a Free Peoples card from hand <br />
here to prevent all wounds to that Dwarf.<br />
Twilight Cost: 0<br />
<br />
This card is obviously meant to be played in a Dwarf deck. An exertion and a FPs card from hand to keep a Dwarf wound free is not a bad deal. You can potentially prevent multiple wounds with this card. I know. It’s not quite as good as Armor or Gimli’s Helm, but for Dwarves other than Gimli, who can’t bear them, it’s probably the next best thing.<br />
By playing plenty of events (in case you get Grima bombed), to keep your Dwarves safely away from overwhelming territory, you can escape battles without having to worry about surprise cards like We Are The Fighting Uruk-hai or Lurtz’s Battle Cry or other annoyances like that while potentially clogging their hand with such cards. In addition, this is also hand control. Getting rid of useless FPs will mean drawing more minions in the long run when you even up. Besides, exerting is always better than letting things fly and taking a wound (provided you weren’t going to discard Dwarven Bracers). You don’t want to run the risk of losing a companion you can heal later. Dwarves, after all, do have a better healing engine than any other culture. <br />
<br />
Gimli, Lockbearer (unique)<br />
Dwarven Companion. Dwarf<br />
Damage +1. Gimli is strength +1 for each<br />
unbound hobbit you can spot.<br />
Twilight Cost: 2<br />
Strength: 6<br />
Vitality: 3<br />
Signet: Aragorn<br />
<br />
A valid companion that, if paired with both merry and pippin, is automatically 8 strength, as compared with Son of Gloin who has to exert to get that. When paired with Legolas, DH, you could possibly use the Final Count, Axe is Notched combo. This Gimli is more likely to win with his 8 (10 with his Axe) and, thus, more likely to place tokens. Also, condition discard or shadow skirmish boosters are less likely to be played as they would cost +2 extra. Also, he has the Aragorn signet, making him applicable with Hard Choice, King in Exile, etc… <br />
<br />
Gimli, Unbidden Guest (unique)<br />
Dwarven Companion. Dwarf<br />
Damage +1. Skirmish: Exert Gimli to make an<br />
unbound companion strength +1 (or +2 if that <br />
companion is Legolas).<br />
Twilight Cost: 2<br />
Strength: 6<br />
Vitality: 3<br />
Signet: Gandalf<br />
<br />
The new common version of Gimli and the new common Legolas were obviously made to work together. Unbidden Guest sports the Gandalf signet making him a good pick for Trust Me. The main difference between him and Son of Gloin who also has the Gandalf signet is that this Gimli gives the +2 strength to Legolas instead of himself. He can, however, give a lesser +1 strength to any other unbound companion including himself. Not a big deal, but that +1 may mean the difference between a won or lost skirmish. Legolas, EC and Gimli, UG do pretty much the same thing except that Legolas decreases minions’ strength, while Gimli increases companions’ strength. All in all, it’s a matter of preference. Son of Gloin with Gimli’s Helm just can’t be beaten when it comes to higher strength, more damaging minions, but Unbidden Guest is better for fellowship support.<br />
<br />
Here Is Good Rock (unique)<br />
Dwarven Condition<br />
Tale. Plays to your support area. Skirmish: Stack a <br />
Free Peoples card from hand here to make a Dwarf damage +1.<br />
Twilight Cost: 1<br />
<br />
Well, this card is obviously not incredibly great. After all, you could just pay 1 more to play Lord of Moria to give every dwarf damage +1, but, once again, like From the Armory, you can use it for hand control. The damage +1 could prove to be quite useful in situations where you’d want to move again, getting rid of excess minions is important. Also, it’s a Tale and believe me, you’re better off using this then Stairs of Khazad-dum.<br />
<br />
Khazad Ai-menu<br />
Dwarven Event<br />
Skirmish: Make a Dwarf strength +2 (or strength +3 <br />
and damage +1 if you can spot Legolas).<br />
Twilight Cost: 1<br />
<br />
As I had mentioned before, this and Best Company are both good choices for Dwarven events. This event may be better if you can keep Legolas alive the whole game. That’s not always an easy task. This card gives you damage +1 instead of the extra strength +1.<br />
In my opinion, this is cool if you’re not toting Gimli’s Axe, but if you are just using Gimli and are also using his Axe, he is already damage +2, so the damage bonus doesn’t help that much. Also, this card costs 1 as opposed to Best Company which costs 0. However, I still think that it’s a great event and if it works for you, that’s great.<br />
<br />
My Axe is Notched (unique)<br />
Dwarven Condition.<br />
Plays to your support area. Each time Gimli wins a <br />
Skirmish, place a [Dwarf] token on this card. While<br />
You can spot X [Dwarf] tokens on this card and same<br />
number of [Elf] tokens on Final Count, Gimli is<br />
strength +X (limit +3).<br />
Twilight Cost: 1<br />
<br />
This card is great for Gimli as practically every version of him is built to win skirmishes. You can win them pretty fast if properly armed. However, in order to use this card, the same number of tokens must be on Final Count meaning that Legolas has to win just as many skirmishes and Legolas isn’t exactly built to win. The two common versions are probably the best, though as Gimli and Legolas can offer support to each other when needed. Giving Gimli his Axe and other support and giving Legolas support like Asfaloth, Long Knives, Bow, you can win the skirmishes fairly quickly. Yes, it can be discarded, but every condition is vulnerable and you don’t lose anything for taking the risk, so why not put these two in?<br />
<br />
Quick As May Be<br />
Dwarven Event<br />
Manuever: Spot a Dwarf companion and an Elf <br />
companion to wound a minion.<br />
Twilight Cost: 1<br />
<br />
I say, any card that deals wounds in the maneuver can’t be that bad. This requires two different culture companions. Obviously, Gimli and Legolas are the prime candidates for this card. It’s kind of like Defend It and Hope except it doesn’t require an exertion. This can be a great bit of anti-Grima tech. The best way, though, to deal with Grima, in my opinion, in a Dwarf deck is packing elf allies and Foul Creation. Sting their hand every turn and if Grima’s there, use FC. Sorry, I know that’s a little bit off the subject, but I know the question’s been bothering you. QAMB is like a little bit of aimed archery except it’s not archery. It’s maneuver. A free wound in the maneuver may make this card worth playing, especially with multiple copies, it can be lethal.<br />
<br />
Rest By Blind Night<br />
Dwarven Event<br />
Regroup: Shuffle any number of [Dwarf] conditions<br />
(and all cards stacked on them) into your draw deck.<br />
Twilight Cost: 0<br />
<br />
This card will be one of the focal points of Dwarven stacking. You can cycle back unwanted cards without discarding them. It’s pretty obvious, though. If you want the card(s) back in your draw deck, use this card. If you don’t want the card(s) back in your draw deck, use Axe of Erebor to get rid of it. Why not shuffle back a Dwarven Heart...right when you’ve healed those wounds so you don’t have to worry about future exertions. Want those minions on EMHR back in there. It’s done. You want those cards you stacked on Here is Good Rock or From the Armory back? You can do that too.<br />
<br />
Restless Axe<br />
Dwarven Event<br />
Regroup: Exert a Dwarf to shuffle a [Dwarf] condition<br />
(and all cards stacked on it) into your draw deck. Exert<br />
a minion for each card shuffled into your draw deck.<br />
Twilight Cost: 2<br />
<br />
This is, in some ways, better than RBBN. While you can only shuffle one Dwarven condition and it costs 2, but it exerts for each card. Dealing exertions in the regroup could be very helpful in double moving if you have other cards that wound minions in the regroup. For example, Calaglin can deal 2 wounds in the regroup, thus, you can exhaust 2 minions and wound them with Calaglin. Notice that there is no limit to how many exertions you can deal. That means if you are dissatisfied with the cards on EMHR, you can shuffle them back AND deal 6 exertions. If you have Gondor companions, by chance, in your deck, Pursuit Just Behind would be an excellent card to go with this.<br />
<br />
Search Far and Wide<br />
Dwarven Event<br />
Fellowship: Spot a Dwarf and discard the top card<br />
of your draw deck to draw 2 cards.<br />
Twilight Cost: 0<br />
<br />
I think the main thing to consider when approaching this card is to compare it to Delving. In many ways, I think it’s better, chiefly because it doesn’t require an exertion. It draws 1 less card, but in my opinion, giving a wound to one of your Dwarves is not worth the extra card. The fact that you don’t have to exert means that this could be useful in decks that aren’t completely dwarves. You could use it in any large deck that uses Gimli. Drawing cards is never a bad thing (unless , of course, if the unthinkable occurs and your opponent is playing Mordor with Verily I Come). Otherwise, you’re good. Also, it costs 0 to Delving’s 1. Ok, 1 twilight difference may not seem like it would make much of a difference, but if it’s in the fellowship phase, it does. <br />
<br />
Stout and Strong (unique)<br />
Dwarven Condition<br />
Plays to your support area. Each time a Dwarf wins<br />
a skirmish, you may place a [Dwarf] token on this<br />
card. Skirmish: Make an unbound companion strength<br />
+1 for each [Dwarf] token here (limit +3) Discard<br />
this condition.<br />
Twilight Cost: 0<br />
<br />
The first thing that you should notice when examining this card is that it costs 0 in comparison with the other token discard conditions that cost 2. It’s not quite as good because it can only give a max of +3 strength. This is probably better off used in a Dwarf deck because you have more Dwarves to win, but it’s kind of nice because it’s like a strength bonus event that you can use whenever you want to. However, a skilled player could use this in a deck that is not Dwarf related. It could be quite helpful as it can give the bonus to any unbound companion. You’d just have to find a reliable way to get Gimli to win all his skirmishes.<br />
<br />
Well, we’ve finally made it to the end. Hope you didn’t fall asleep. Since I was writing this deck, I’ve eventually ended up contradicting myself in the first 2 paragraphs. There, I mentioned that this was dedicated to the revival of Dwarf decks and I still hope to see them, but actually, I ended up mentioning use of Dwarf cards outside of Dwarf decks. <br />
<br />
Well, I’m done now. Also, if you have any combos, uses, etc… about the cards that I listed that I did not mention, you are most welcome to include them in the reviews. The main point of this is, as always, to build a better game. I’m not saying everyone should use Dwarf decks, but, hey, it would hurt to try, right?<br />
<br />
